Comment:
*This is the true story:* 

The truth is that in the 70s, the Warrens went to that house and some weird stuff happened supposedly but that whole aspect about demons was completely made up. And there's no proof that lady who once lived there killed her children. In fact there's no proof that she had more than a single child and that's not even the one who died. Another person's child died in her care (sewing needle in the back of its head) and she was accused of being a witch and was ultimately acquitted however her reputation was hindered by it so she became a recluse afterwards for the rest of her life and that's literally it.¬†She was not hung and did not kill herself or "profess her love for satan".  The Warrens did not perform an exorcism. In fact they did not help at all they just made everything temporarily worse. So all the Warrens did was go to the house, get scared and that's all. 

The rotting meat smell supposedly did happen and the mother was apparently coming off as "possessed" for a time there but not this intensely. Everything else that happened was truly just normal paranormal type stuff. And that was back in the 70s. The current owners now insist that the house is only mildly haunted and maintain that nothing about it is negative and hate all the publicity surrounding it.

The most wild and intense ghost encounter (from the 1970s occurrences) was not even portrayed or shown in the film. It was when the mother saw a woman wearing grey at the edge of her bed telling her that she will "drive her out with death and gloom". Reading into the history, it seems like the Warrens were nothing more than a blip on the radar for this house's history. They didn't provide anything useful and the family continued to live there for years just dealing with it.

Though the nightmares don‚Äôt bother me anymore. It was a matter of figuring out exactly where it originated from, and figuring out specifically what insecurities I possessed. It was like a puzzle. Comment: I loved this movie, but in reality aren't Ed and Lorraine Warren KNOWN to be frauds? I mean it's obvious that none of this fairytale garbage is actually true, but I remember hearing about a relative of someone who Ed and Lorraine said needed an exorcism who sued them both because the so-called possessed person actually needed medical attention. And another person who went to write a book about the people who supposedly experienced the haunting in Connecticut noticed that many family members seemed quite disturbed (so perhaps needing psychological help and not frikking 'mediums') and they couldn't keep a consistent story. And when he told Ed this, Ed allegedly responded 'make the rest up and make it scary.' This is still one of the best horror movies I've ever experienced, but that doesn't mean that any of the crap in it is even close to being actual facts.

There is usually a pretty big difference between inspired by a true story and based on a true story. Works that are inspired by a true story get the background from something that actually happened, but rarely ever stay true to what actually happened. When something is based on true story, it is usually more fact than fiction.

Not saying that this story is 100% true. But it's probably more true than you'd think. :)
